:"Carrick, Ayrshire, Skotland","Scotland":"Skotland, United Kingdom","Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas, Lanarkshire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1317–1360":"1317–1360","1320–1384":"1320–1384","1311–1333":"1311–1333","1334–1368":"1334–1368","1368–Male":"1368–Overleden","1368":"1368","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1311":"1311","ABT 1333":"circa 1333","1320":"1320","19 JUL 1333":"19 juli 1333","about 1334":"circa 1334","1384":"1384","1360":"1360","1317":"1317","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Berwick-upon-tweed, Northumberland, England":"Berwick-upon-Tweed, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas, Lanarkshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1317–1360":"1317–1360","1320–1384":"1320–1384","1311–1333":"1311–1333","1334–1368":"1334–1368","1368–Male":"1368–Deceased","1368":"1368","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1311":"1311","ABT 1333":"about 1333","1320":"1320","19 JUL 1333":"19 July 1333","about 1334":"about 1334","1384":"1384","1360":"1360","1317":"1317","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Berwick-upon-tweed, Northumberland, England":"Berwick-upon-Tweed, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Douglas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from any of various places called from their situation on a river named with Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black’ + <i>glas</i> ‘stream’ (a derivative of <i>glas</i> ‘blue’). There are several localities in Scotland and Ireland so named, but the one from which the surname is derived in most if not all cases is Douglas in Lanarkshire 20 miles south of Glasgow, the original stronghold of the influential Douglas family and their retainers.","History: The family taking their name from Douglas in Lanarkshire were of Flemish origin. They rose to great prominence in the 14th and 15th centuries, controlling the earldoms of Douglas, Morton, and Angus, and later, Queensberry."],"variants":[{"name":"Douglass","meanings":["Scottish and English (Durham and Northumbria): variant of   Douglas  .","History: William Douglass, a physician recognized for his identification and description of an epidemic of scarlet fever, was born <i>c.</i> 1691 in Gifford, Haddington County, Scotland, and settled in Boston in 1718. The abolitionist, orator, and journalist Frederick Douglass assumed the name after escaping from slavery in 1838 and traveling to Massachusetts. Son of a white father and a slave with some Indian blood, he was born Frederick Augustus Washington Bailey <i>c.</i> 1817 in Tuckahoe, MD."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Douglas was born in 1317, in Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. She married Alexander Bruce 1st and last Earl of Carrick about 1333, in Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1360, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1317–1360":"1317–1360","1320–1384":"1320–1384","1311–1333":"1311–1333","1334–1368":"1334–1368","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","1368":"1368","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1311":"1311","ABT 1333":"umbes 1333","1320":"1320","19 JUL 1333":"19. juuli 1333","about 1334":"umbes 1334","1384":"1384","1360":"1360","1317":"1317","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Berwick-upon-tweed, Northumberland, England":"Berwick-upon-Tweed, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Douglas, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Douglas, Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1317–1360":"1317–1360","1320–1384":"1320–1384","1311–1333":"1311–1333","1334–1368":"1334–1368","1368–Male":"1368–Kuollut","1368":"1368","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1311":"1311","ABT 1333":"noin 1333","1320":"1320","19 JUL 1333":"19. heinäkuuta 1333","about 1334":"noin 1334","1384":"1384","1360":"1360","1317":"1317","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Berwick-upon-tweed, Northumberland, England":"Berwick-upon-Tweed, Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yh